        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity:
========

We request an rms sensitivity of 128 mK for a spectral resolution of 2.5 km/s (see below for details of the 0.488 MHz channel spacing with which we will observe). This will provide a s/n of &gt;3.5 per 2.5 km/s channel, using very conservative assumptions (see scientific justification). Under typical conditions we expect and given the clustered nature of the CO emission on these scales, this will likely be much higher. Most importantly, however, resolving the CO line (line width ~10km/s) is only a secondary objective. Our primary interest is to map the CO emission and resolve it spatially, for which we can bin spectrally to 10 km/s to a s/n of &gt;7 even under conservative assumptions. 

At 1" resolution, necessary to probe spatial scales similar to those on which the stars typically cluster in our HST data, the beam size corresponds to the size of the low-mass star forming region Taurus (~20pc) at 4.5Mpc and we could easily resolve the Orion molecular cloud (100pc). Expected integrated intensities for such clouds (with masses ~5*10^4 and 2*10^5 M_sol, respectively) and our beam size yield ~4.5 K km/s (assuming twice the Galactic X_CO, a conservative
estimate given observations in the LMC at similar metallicity finding a close-to Galactic X_CO, e.g. Hughes et al. 2013). 
For a typical line width of 10km/s and requiring to detect the line at 7 sigma thus requires sigma T_MB ~ 64 mK over 10 km/s.
Under conservative assumptions (no structured emission/peaks, high X_CO, this translates to &gt;3.5 sigma per 2.5 km/s channel, very likely a lower limit on the S/N. 
Most importantly, however, spectrally resolving the CO line 
is only a secondary objective. Our primary interest is to map the CO emission and resolve it spatially, for which we can bin spectrally to 10 km/s to achieve a S/N of 7 at the very least. 
According to the OT, the total observing time including overheads is 3.7 hr.

At the same time, we will detect continuum emission at a (1 sigma) sensitivity of 0.01 mJy/beam.


Imaging
========

We wish to image one target field in the 12CO J=1-0 transition at 1'' angular resolution (C34-4 configuration). With 1.92 hours on-source integration time we will achieve a good uv-coverage for imaging.

Correlator Setup
===========

We wish to observe the CO J=1-0 line (rest frequency 115.27 GHz), in Band 3, using a bandwidth of 937.5 MHz and 0.488 MHz (1.27 km/s at the distance of M83) spectral resolution (including online Hanning smoothing). Since M83 is a very nearby galaxy (radial velocities for the two pointings are ~500-600 km/s) this is the coarsest spectral resolution FDM mode that is achievable without the spectral window falling out of the edge of the band. We estimate detected line widths to be ~10 km/s, and so will smooth our data into 2.5 km/s channels. We expect this to provide a s/n &gt;3.5 per 2.5 km/s channel (see above), but in case additional sensitivity is needed and because spectrally resolving the line is not critical for our science case, we can smooth to a velocity resolution of 10 km/s.

In addition to the one spectral window which we will place on the CO J=1-0 line, we will use the remaining three spectral windows (2 GHz bandwidth TDM mode spectral windows, which have 31.25 MHz channel spacing) to obtain the continuum emission. The continuum will be obtained over a total of 7.5 GHz, omitting the spectral lines in the band.


Calibration
========

We require standard observatory-defined calibration.


Bandpass accuracy
============

We do not require higher than standard bandpass accuracy to achieve our science goals.


Scheduling/Time constraints
===================

There are no special scheduling/time constraints.


Data rates
========

Our spectral setups do not require higher than average data rates.


Special constraints on standard observing modes
========

None.</prj:justificationText>
