    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>In order to understand the conditions that lead to star formation in the extreme outskirts (&gt;2*r_25) of galaxies, we propose to map CO emission in a star-forming knot in the outer disk of the nearby spiral galaxy M83. In addition to bright UV emission and decent nebular metallicities (~1/2 solar),  our target region coincides with peaks of atomic gas and hot dust emission. Our team furthermore led an HST proposal to obtain resolved stellar photometry, which reveal ongoing massive star formation. This implies that star forming molecular gas is being actively cycled into stars. In order to make a first complete characterization of this gas in an outer galaxy disk, on scales comparable to the clustering scale of individual stars in our HST data (~1"), the key missing ingredient is the distribution of the molecular gas, which only ALMA can provide. This is a key measurement, because most theories  regarding where star formation can and cannot proceed in outer galaxy disks (i.e., proposed "star formation thresholds") and thus how galactic disks can grow, focus on the ability to form molecular clouds. However, the molecular gas in these regions has so far gone largely unobserved.</prp:abstract>
